            <div type="witness" subtype="essay">
                <pb facs="MSVIII60v"/>
                <head type="title"><space quantity="16" unit="chars" /><handShift new="#HANDJR1833-34" script="cursive" medium="ink"/>The <geogName corresp="#MEUSE">Meuse</geogName></head>
                    <p>How <del rend="strikethrough">be</del> lightly the waves of the broad <geogName corresp="#MEUSE">Meuse</geogName>, crisped<lb/> 
                        with the first breath of the morning, as we swept over<lb/>
                        the long bridge that crosses the river from <placeName corresp="#NAMUR">Namur</placeName>,<lb/> 
                        and looked back on the rich dome of its small, but<lb/> 
                        beautiful cathedral,<ref type="gloss_contextual" target="the_meuse_glosses_contextual.php#LONGBRIDGEGLOSS"/> as it began to smile to the<lb/> 
                        first glance <del rend="strikethrough">th</del> of the joyous sun, that was drink&#x2010;<lb/> 
                        ing up the delicate mists, which clung to the hills and<lb/> 
                        rested <subst><del>i</del><add rend="overwriting">o</add></subst>n the valley in which the fair city reposed<lb/> 
                        so peacefully, and then <del rend="strikethrough">plunged</del> dashed along the<lb/> 
                        valley of the <geogName corresp="#MEUSE">Meuse</geogName>. I know not, if it was because<lb/> 
                        this was our first initiation into the scenery of<lb/> 
                        continental rivers, but this part of the <geogName corresp="#MEUSE">Meuse</geogName><lb/> 
                        appeared to me infinitely preferable, (not in point<lb/> 
                        of sublimity, or immensity but in that romantic<lb/> 
                        and picturesque fairy beauty, which is, in many<lb/>
                        cases preferable to either) to any thing which I ever<lb/> 
                        afterwards saw on the shores of the farfamed <geogName corresp="#RHINE">Rhine</geogName>.<lb/> 
                        There was, to me, a great sameness throughout the whole<lb/> 
                        of the &#x2038; <add place="above"><space quantity="7" unit="chars"/>course of the</add> latter river, and &#x2038; <add place="above"><space quantity="25" unit="chars"/>as</add> to its fortresses, it is positively too<lb/> 
                        much of a good thing, a tiresome repitition of ruins,<lb/> 
                        and ruins too, which do not altogether come up to my<lb/> 
                        idea of what ruins ought to be,<ref type="gloss_textual" target="the_meuse_prose_glosses_textual.php#TERMINALCOMMA" /> But for the <geogName corresp="#MEUSE">Meuse</geogName>,<lb/> 
                        the infinite variety of scenery, the almost confusing<lb/> 
                        succession of delightful changes, the impossibility of <del rend="strikethrough">examining</del> <add place="below"><space quantity="57" unit="chars"/>seeing</add><lb/>
                    <pb facs="MSVIII61r"/>
                        <fw type="pageNum" place="top-right"><handShift new="#HANDWGC" medium="pencil"/>61</fw>
                        <handShift new="#HANDJR1833-34" script="cursive" medium="ink"/>every successive change as you feel that it ought to be seen, and<lb/> 
                        finally, the tantalizing rate at which you dash away (capital<lb/> 
                        road) from that which you could feast upon, and look upon<lb/> 
                        and dwell upon, for&#x2014;ages I was going to say, months, I<lb/> 
                        will say, are enough to enchant you with anything.  If you<lb/> 
                        wish to see rock scenery in perfection, go to the <geogName corresp="#MEUSE">Meuse</geogName>,<ref type="gloss_contextual" target="the_meuse_glosses_contextual.php#GOTOTHEMEUSEGLOSS"/> for<lb/> 
                        never were rocks more beautifully disposed, more richly and<lb/> 
                        delicately wooded or more finely contrasted with the amaz&#x2010;<lb/>
                        ing luxuriance of&#x2038; <add place="above"><space quantity="19" unit="chars"/>the</add> surrounding scenery. But alas. it was<lb/> 
                        but a forenoon ride, and the eve saw us quit the magnificent<lb/>
                        <geogName corresp="#MEUSE">Meuse</geogName> with sorrow for the smoky streets and coal wharfs<lb/>
                        of <placeName corresp="#LIEGE">Liege</placeName>, and the round, dumpy, shapeless hills of <placeName corresp="#SPA">Spa</placeName>.<ref type="gloss_contextual" target="the_meuse_glosses_contextual.php#LIEGESPAGLOSS"/><lb/></p>
                       
